{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S1MTpbfGuTeHWR2vbRfE1v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that `elasticsearch-keystore` tries to parse `elasticsearch.yml`, and it contains `${POD_NAME}` which is resolved from the `POD_NAME` environment variable. But the init container doesn't have this env var.\n\nI need to either:\n1. Set the `POD_NAME` env var in the init container\n2. Use a simpler elasticsearch.yml in the init container for the keystore operation\n3. Use a different approach to avoid the POD_NAME placeholder issue\n\nActually, the simplest fix is to set `POD_NAME` env var in the init container. The keystore doesn't need the elasticsearch.yml to be fully resolved - it just needs to parse it. \n\nThe real problem is that the keystore binary fails when it encounters unresolved placeholders like `${POD_NAME}`. I could set a dummy value for `POD_NAME` in the init container, skip copying the configmap's elasticsearch.yml and use the image's default instead, or create a stripped-down version of the config without the placeholder for the keystore creation step.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to create the keystore using the image's default elasticsearch.yml (which won't have the `${POD_NAME}` placeholder), then copy the keystore to the output directory afterward. The image's default config is clean and won't cause parsing errors.\n\nWriting init script... Writing shell script...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":573,"cache_read_input_tokens":60548,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":573},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"345750bd-2903-4710-8544-c47b8be95c0c","uuid":"0867e69a-5e7c-4b2e-bcc3-bea55e24ce0c",